% Just for fun I asked several llm's in illama and the results were kind of
% disappointing. Qwen (basic) was kind of fast but kept hallucinating about what
% cubes to drop, starting over and over again with different drops. The larger 32
% model did a better job but seems to use some Lua stuff not in the language. The
% 72 model was so slow on my machine that it is kind of useless. Even the base model
% reminds one of the early \TEX\ days. Other llm's were unuseable too. In the end
% Chat 5.5 (which I can't afford) and Google in the browser were mostly. Here's a
% snippet of qwen32 when I asked where it got "step" from:
%
%     By using the `step` metamethod, the code can efficiently create a sequence of
%     coordinates to access the sub-cubes in the Menger sponge algorithm without
%     explicitly defining separate loops for corners, edges, and center cubes. This
%     makes the code more concise and easier to understand.
%
%     >>> as far as i can see there is no "step" in lua 5.5 so where did you read
%     that
%
%     Apologies for the confusion. I apologize for the error in my previous
%     response. The `step` metamethod does not exist in Lua by default. Instead, we
%     should use a standard `for` loop with an increment operator to achieve the
%     same effect. Here's how you can modify the code to use regular loops:
%
%     Replace the following lines:
%     ```lua
%     for dz in offset[1]:step(3, edge_length) do
%         for dy in offset[2]:step(3, edge_length) do
%             for dx in offset[3]:step(3, edge_length) do
%     ```
%     With this block:
%     ```lua
%     for dz = offset[1], edge_length - 1, 3 do
%         for dy = offset[2], edge_length - 1, 3 do
%             for dx = offset[3], edge_length - 1, 3 do
%
% Now ask yourself, does the first blob really looks more concise and better? It
% will be slower for sure. Anyway: "How does one generate a menger sponge mesh in
% Lua" makes a nice test because somehow all these models know a bit about it. As
% far as I'm concerned, only a few got it kind of right, and even then one had to
% unslop the code.
%
% Then I tried Qwen3-Coder-Next-GGUF in Unsloth and that not only ran reasonable
% fast but also started to generate code that worked, although I ran into context
% length limits (\TEX\ doesn't pay for a hardware upgrade.) But apart from adding
% extra unmatched braces that invalidated \LUA\ tables it also messed up the
% normals. Some comments suggested that all used used the same Python code as
% template. So, basically a wasted day. Interesting was that the models agreed in
% errors that one points out. In the end on can best just write such code from
% scratch when the basic algorithm is known.
